author: UCy9OdwtriPbMvcG7Xi5asMw
comment: @Ash  you don't need a whole lot of special tools. Josh is a professional so he has pro tools but you don't need them.  The most important thing is to get a very sharp, 6 or 8 in. chef's knife.Then get a smaller paring knife for cutting up small fruits or garlic.   Next you should buy a 10 or 12 in. stainless steel skillet, a large stainless steel pot for soups, smaller stainless steel pot for pasta/rice, and maybe a smaller pan for frying eggs. Get some wood or bamboo spatulas and stirring spoons so you don't scratch up your pots/pans. Get two strainers (large one, and a smaller one) for draining frying oil and a lodge cast iron pan.. For baking, use a 9 x 13 pyrex for large casseroles or bread loaves. Then for baking brownies, use a much smaller pyrex. Then get a set of stainless steel or glass mixing bowls and a whisk.  Now you can make almost anything. This is the exact setup I use for 95% of my recipes on a daily basis. My stainless steel setup is a set from Belique and my glass mixing bowls are anchor hocking.

author: UChg7e3cD1WSH8MtVZAMrpUw
comment: I love the idea of but cheaper, you can customize your food in many ways, that your imagination and your talent is the limit. But, the problem is that there are some restaurants that tends to struggle because of the produce and meats they get in. A lot of restaurants don't get the luxury of getting fresh produce every day. Some delivery companies tends to bring in produce that's not the best, and even the companies that sells the freshest produce can be quite expensive, which is why many businesses tends to go for the cheaper varieties in order to meet up with the demand.   Supply and demand is also another problem too. There's folks that would like many restaurants to keep a food that they like at a certain low price, which explains why restaurants prefer cheaper produce and meats to keep the food at such low price.   Labor cost is also another problem. The demand for higher payment and benefits are all over the place. Which requires many employers to pay their employees higher pay checks when they struggle on their own. That can also add up on why a delicious breakfast sandwich would cost between $8 to $12, depending on where you're at. It's true here in the states, people can't survive on minimum wage alone, and have to work two or three jobs just to pay bills.  The last thing that adds up why food at restaurants are expensive, are bills. Not only restaurants has to deal with produce and meats and waste on what can't be used. But, they have to deal with labor cost, supply and demand. And bills, such as utilities, electrical, gas, etc. And here in the states, we got big electrical and gas companies that are pretty greedy and would charge more than what is worth. I'm sure there are other gas and electrical companies in other countries that are greedy as well.  Making it at home can be cheaper in the long run, and you can customize it the way you want. And you don't have to pay anyone to make it either or worry about supply and demand other than what you want. But, what I say about the restaurants is true. I know, I used to be a top manager at a large liquor store/ pizza joint.

author: UCeArF7jgbyQI_urIx20Ju0g
comment: Just watched this video. I think you missed one important step, the creation of "the drip." The drip is an expression used by pro cheesemakers for the moistening juice which flavors and keeps the cheesesteak juicy throughout its consumption. It is created by circling the cheesesteak when the meat is cooked but before the cheese is placed on the meat. Take a squeeze bottle of water and circle the meat with a good spray. Put on the cheese and cover the meat and cheese with a domed cover. This will cause the cheese to be melted by the steam and will create a delicious juice which will be scooped up and wet the roll eliminating the need for mayo (mayo is a travesty to Philly cheesesteak eaters). The magical juice created by that water is a key ingredient to an authentic Philly cheesesteak. Had you gotten to John's or D'Aleesandro's you would have seen it being done. Try it again and send out a report.

author: UCm2_GunzMRyUmLQAW1wlj5g
comment: As someone from Philly, to answer your final question: Yes, I think you paid proper respect to our cheese steaks. That shit looks amazing!  It's a shame you didn't get to hit Dalessandro's, but at least you got to Max's. Though I was surprised nobody recommended Jim's to you. And, yes, usually if somebody asks us if we prefer Pat's or Geno's our response tends to be, "Don't be a tourist," followed by our personal favorite recommendation.  Super impressed with the roll you made. A lot of us will tell you it must be an Amaroso Roll (myself included), or at least something made in Philly, but I think you taking the extra step to make the roll yourself is valid. Anybody comes at you for that can shut up.  You get points for the Provolone, the original cheese for the Philly cheese steak. Though most places will put the roll over the steak at the end to help it melt, and kind of crisp up the bread. But no worries if you don't.  I have heard this tall tale of putting mayo on a cheese steak, but everybody I have asked from Philly gives me a look of disgust when I brought it up. And the more I looked into it, the general consensus is "Gross, no". So I'ma have to take a point off for mayo. BUT JUST ONE POINT. Getting a score of 99 is still a really good grade! author: UCDbOGqIV9rAxQFj1LNJq3gA
comment: Measuring in grams, makes the recipe repeatable.  As a metrics nerd, i have measured in volume (cups of flour), and found 10 percent variation... with grams, it is spot on.. every time. Once you get the hang of taring out your scale after each addition, you eliminate extra dirty dishes.. Add flour, tare.. add salt, tare, likewise the rest of the dry ingredients.  A little scared you might over due it.. ok, do those in a separate dish, then add it to the flour.  try it... its really not that difficult.  Do not know what the conversion is from cups to grams... King Arthur Flour website has a table I trust. BTW, their bread flour is rather pleasant.  I use it 50 50 with AP.

author: UCtA9njD8t5-19skZh0GTrvg
comment: That is if your digital ‚Äútareable‚Äù scale is actually repeatable which is after buying a half of dozen digital scales of various brand names on them that were all made in China that after just a few month of use I purchased an old mechanical bakers scale (balance) (you know the ones that you stack weights on one side and ingredients on the otZdhers side and when the left and right pan or the needle in the middle is vertical you have the correct weight. As for balance weights I purchased some and I cast some out of lead-free pewter and if need some oddball weight I can always use a graduated cylinder and water because after all a Milliliter of water and a Gram of water weights the same just like a Pint (of water weighs) a Pound the world around.  As for flour my goto A/P flour is Wheat Montana it‚Äôs less expensive than King Arthur‚Äôs and in my personal opinion is as good if not better and for bread flour I buy 50lb bags of either King Arthur‚Äôs Sir Lancelot or General Mills All Trumps and store it in food grade 5 gallon buckets not only do I like better than other Bread flours you can buy in 5, 8, or 10 pound bags but the cost per poEund/kilo is generally less expensive as well. I also buy Rye flour in 20 to 30 pound bags because the otherwise the price per ounce/pound is absolutely stupidly expensive. I divide Rye flour up into gallon zip-top bags and freeze it to keep it fresh.

author: UCtA9njD8t5-19skZh0GTrvg
comment: My dinner roll recipe is similar except I use two eggs and one egg yolk that I whisk in my sugar into (actually a 50/40/10 mix of granulated sugar/honey/light brown sugar (Note if you don‚Äôt like brown sugar reduce it by half or omit it and replace it with granulated sugar) I then mix the egg/sugar into my scalded milk. Normally I don‚Äôt use dry yeast but rather 100g of my ripe Sourdough starter however if I want a quick rise I proof my dry yeast only in water with a pinch of sugar and flour.  Additionally I don‚Äôt use melted butter but knead softened butter in one ‚Äúpat‚Äù at time into my dough. Lastly I very lightly mist my rolls with milk just prior to baking and since I don‚Äôt buy salted butter I mix Kosher salt that I have powdered into my unsalted butter a little at a time until desired flavor is obtained and then top my rolls with flakes of salt that I make using a saturated salt solution and a jelly pan on my grill using corn cobs and walnut shells for smoke.  As for Honey butter don‚Äôt like adding confectionery sugar or vanilla into it for toast, rolls, or biscuits use but for pancakes and waffles that‚Äôs another story.  I feel the confectionery sugar make the butter to sweet and the vanilla takes away from the taste of my butter.  I make my butter with heavy whipping cream I purchase from a local dairy using my stand mixer (I could spent a bunch time describing how I do it but watch John Kirkwood video on how he makes his butter and it‚Äôs the basically identical) after I wash my butter I clean my mixer and put the whip and bowl in the freezer for a 20 to 30 minutes and then while the butter is soft whip honey that I get from my.neighbor who keeps bees (my preferred honey is from the hives he keeps on some swampland along the Chesapeake bay the brackish water that the bees ‚Äúdrink‚Äù and clover, wildflowers, honeysuckle, etc the bees feed on has a hint salty funky flavor that you might not want to put on ice cream or in your tea but in honey butter it‚Äôs absolutely delicious but since honey like that is not readily available and it‚Äôs flavor might not be for everyone any good high quality honey will work but seriously if you can buy honey from a local bee keepers spend the few bucks more at least once and give it a try.  My neighbor also has bees on strawberry farm and the honey that those hives produce taste faintly of strawberries and is delicious on biscuits or scones  PS if you grease a clean Iron Skillet and place 50 to 60 grams balls of the above dough about 3/8‚Äù apart and then proof with a light greased piece of plastic wrap (I use the plastic bags (spit them of course) you put your produce in at the grocery store) loosely over them while proofing) makes for great for share/tear-apart rolls that are always a great thing for a family dinner, dinner party, or holiday meal. You can use a regular skillet but a square cornbread skillet works even better.

author: UC87vrBqxbu_kojtiVQ06BjQ
comment: Great recipe, and quite authentic. The sauce is superbly good, even if you don‚Äôt have all the exact ingredients.   For all those who struggle getting ingredients: use spaghetti instead of udon. Yes, not the same but it works. I think I also once read that if you add baking soda to the cooking water it will add the chewy texture. Those sugar bulbs you can swap for brown or even white sugar, dark soy sauce tastes the same as normal soy sauce, it‚Äôs mostly visual. Mirin can be substituted for white wine and sugar, rice vinegar can be replaced with the mildest white vinegar in your house but watered down to 30-50% concentration while keeping the total quantity.Shirodashi is made of seaweed, you could make your own from kombu algae but to keep it quick and simple add more msg, both ultimately are umami flavours. Oyster sauce is tricky, but luckily it‚Äôs getting more popular and available. Comment if you know how to substitute that one ‚ò∫Ô∏è

author: UC3Z_MsWXiW1SFgHMAZtgRqA
comment: @Grabble true, kind of. I've had improvised 'Asian' noodles and they always suck.   If you don't really know exactly why the original ingredients needed to be there and what exact flavors they add, you end up making something entirely different with completely different taste even if it seems like you were altering things slightly  It's one of those things where you really should make it exactly like the recipe the first time, unless you already know what it should taste like.   And then improvise in the future after that. Light and dark soy sauce have very different flavors for example, and depending on the recipe, the texture of different types of sugar can change the end result disastrously.  Beginner cooks should avoid improvising in the beginning and gradually edge towards it imo

author: UCqBzxioFzGTxP9Uf1QCTDUA
comment: @yozypost Udon noodles aren't always thick. The most common "Udon" (both in Japan and outside of Japan) is Sanuki Udon, which is thick and chewy, but there does exist other types of Udon that are thinner or other shapes (like there are lasagna-noodle-shaped Udon as well as ones that look like orecchiette). That said, the sauce he uses and the toppings is much closer to yakisoba than yakiudon.

author: UCibe1wiGj8qolc6SU2UJIbg
comment: To add to this, this recipe is a quick one that seems pretty quick to make. If you really want your marinara sauce to be fantastic, and I mean even better, follow the same recipe, but skip the sugar. instead, add an additional can of crushed san marzano tomatoes (if they're not crushed enough to your liking defo take a potato masher to em'), and a small squeeze of tomato paste. Possibly up the thinly sliced garlic by 1/2, and simmer for 30-45 minutes or until reduced by about half before you add your meatballs back to the sauce to continue cooking. This will result in a chunkier marinara, but the texture is great, and the time you took to simmer it will get rid of the acidity naturally, which will always taste a bit better than adding sugar. It's not a HUGE improvement mind you, but it's noticeable enough that it can be worth it if you have an extra 30-45 minutes to just let it simmer.

author: UCVNk3ofgkGJK9eAVhxiYBrg
comment: Italian cook here, i'm probably biased by the fact that olive oil is cheap over there but i find going a little heavier on oil helps both against the acidic release ( if the tomato is good ), also helping the sauce retain a better textures as opposed to the thick viscous look here, while also better dressing the pasta without being flaky or dry.  Think of oil as tomato protection, if you see oil over the sides of your pan more or less at the same height of your sauce ( once reduced a bit ) you're golden

author: UCDgX6a2kB6JJhTbBz2wdVVA
comment: I‚Äôm Turkish, i will be judging, update coming soon. We Turkish people are very serious about our food. - in the Turkish traditional version we actually use starch in order to prevent sticking and we roll our dough in circles (the shape of the baklava changes regionally and we do include other nuts, according to different provinces. But pistachio is usually the go to) - once we have made around small 5 circles of dough, we stack the circles and very generously dust between layers with starch  - then we roll all the dough together until (as Joshua said) - you can see your fingers through the dough  - other than that, this was a job well done and greatly modified for foreigners, i would say dont even bother with the dough and go for some Turkish ‚ÄúYufka‚Äù if you can find some nice traditional baklava yufka its just as good.

author: UCPFeueWssIK4T_TyCGYZCaA
comment: When combining the pastry with the syrup one of them must be hot and the other one cold normally. Either make the syrup beforehand, let it cool and pour over the baklava as soon as it comes out the oven, or let the baklava cool and then make the syrup. This allows the fylo to soak up more syrup which will make it less crunchy but its the way to go if you wanna make it traditional as far as i know.

author: UCGF20LPXKNsvKxLJW8h9DRw
comment: Thanks for this introductory video to make "home made" baklavas. It definitely seems like a lot of work and research. As a Greek Turk who have lived in both countries, I can say, the Greek version is pretty accurate. Greek recognize baklava more as a homemade dessert with all its imperfections and amateur fashion. Like yours. But in Turkey, the situation is different. Country is filled with speciality shops that's been making baklava since decades, sometimes over a century. The way they perfected that extremely thin crust, the use of fragrant, oily  pistachios from one specific city Gaziantep, ghee sourced from the butter produced in local dairies, and variety of techniques in making carries this thing to another dimension. To me, they both look like a Greek baklava with different fillings and spices. But difference is more than that. Since the concept of authenticity is all about reflecting what's commonly accepted by the locals, let me add that this does not reflect the authentic Turkish baklava that would move Turkish people in the hearth. Easy, but not authentic.

author: UCwTJa4civrhQ_KTmGLgUWPQ
comment: @TissuePaper , this is very true. Greek here, and my family and wy wife's are both very traditional, and they all use store-bought 99% of the time. They will make their own fillo very rarely, and they dispense with the pasta roller and use a super flat wood disc that is wider than a table, and perfectly straight rolling pins. They flour it generously and free it from the surface repeatedly to re-roll and stretch by hand. A pasta roller can't get it thin enough. And even then, they use it mostly for spanakopita, and not baklava, since the texture of store-bought is still better.  He should have shown how to handle store-bought fillo. It needs to be brought up to room temperature slowly, unrolled, and then covered in a slightly damp towel to keep it from drying out and cracking. The layers need to be continuous over the entire span of the baking pan, which is another reason a pasta roller is not a good option. The strips are not wide enough.

author: UCgCr74GlYlJ8PTSMWbEwQEw
comment: @~ random user ~ Thats fair  I'd argue that its not really better then nothing, it is nothing. S&B is a pretty big brand, its japanese, hence why the curry roux you'll get in japan is the same as you get everywhere else, I'm not from the US either.  And really other then what is in Josh's roux, S&B add malic acid as a preservative (Malic acid occurs naturally in pretty much all fruit and in most of them it is the primary source of sourness, except citrus fruit.), and E631 and E627 which are naturally occuring sodium salts that enhance the flavour from MSG. Thats it.  In general a lot of the hubbub people have over additives or flavour enhancers (E631 and E627 arent even considered additives anymore) is a largely manufactured one, and the idea of avoiding these products and instead taking a more time consuming and expensive route out of fear of scary additives is one that while not meant to, can be extremely polarizing to people who for whatever reason cant afford to (money or time)   Idk, food for thought (Food thought)

author: UCiFnp-kan7T6ri33Xc97O2A
comment: A good trick that many Chinese chefs use when making dumplings is that they would mix the meat with the seasoning and marinate first and put the veg on top. Wait until they are ready to fill the dumpling and then mix the meat and veg together, that way the veg won't sit in salt and soy sauce and drain out all their water and won't developed that rotten-like vegetable smell, either.

author: UCDlKsDdXvz1o0nZnYJUmdaA
comment: I had the same annoyance when I started cooking regularly, the reason why it‚Äôs always cheaper is because he generally has this stuff around, this comes from cooking regularly, at first I had nothing so I spent a lot of money getting some pots, pans, utensils and the random ingredients, I buy in bulk so it‚Äôs more expensive at first, but you save an egregious amount of money, I cycle through 30 different meal prep meals and the most expensive one is about 30 dollars for 5 days of food ‚Äî I am a grad student in Astronomy and astrophysics, I take 5 classes, work full time and do research plus I train at 4am daily, so time to cook was something I thought I didn‚Äôt have, but it‚Äôs far less time and costs far less to meal prep and it‚Äôs a lot healthier.  The only downside is eating the same meal a few times in a row, but switching meals weekly can help a ton, but personally I can‚Äôt say much on that because I‚Äôm like a trashcan and just eat to survive   Long story short, you might spend a good chunk of change at first, but you‚Äôll make up for it in savings and start realize how much less you spend, my friends will leave the lab at noon to go get fast food for lunch and won‚Äôt get done for close to 1.5 hours + they spend 10-20 dollars per meal, and my dorky ass pulls out my 2 dollar a meal max meal prep, eats in 20 min cuz I can‚Äôt do two things at once and am back doing work and I either get more done or get out early, I do sacrifice 2 hours cooking the meal prep, but after a couple days I save more time, money and the foods honestly tastes better than fast food imo, I haven‚Äôt eaten a lot of fast food though, I‚Äôve still never been to a Burger King or Wendy‚Äôs, only McDonalds like 7 years ago and chipotle cuz burritos go hard

comment: I literally just made his old dumpling recipe last week‚Ä¶   Some tips:  YOU *WILL NOT* USE ALL OF THE FILLING! YOULL USE HALF, MAYBE 3/4! If you make the pan fried version, adjust the cooking time. Let the bottoms brown for 2 minutes, and add 1/3 cup water to the pan. Let it steam for about 5 minutes. This ensures your pork is cooked! If you don‚Äôt have a pasta extruder don‚Äôt bother making the dough. It takes much longer than it‚Äôs worth to roll it out by hand.  Wonton wrappers work just as well if you can‚Äôt find gyoza wrappers! You don‚Äôt be able to shape it as well because it‚Äôs not the correct shape but it cooks the same way and works just fine. It cooks the same and acts the same.

author: UCn3DxHMbIUcIh-vrVsopk6g
comment: I actually prefer them steamed & purely because of the texture, I like them soft & squishy. There's this restaurant I use to live somewhat close to that made such amazing steamed dumplings, their dough was a little thicker than usual & they were big. Love that sauce too, thanks for showing us how simple the sauce is because every time I went to that restaurant, I'd save the dipping sauce from the dumplings to pour over my rice. It tastes so good! I also like pouring it into that open pocket which oh man, making me crave them. I might just have to try this at home since I no longer live near that restaurant & the restaurants here are.... yeah, there aren't any good Chinese restaurants here which is a shame because it was always my go-to whenever I went to eat out for any special occasion, just miss that one Chinese restaurant with the good dumplings, the owner even knew my family since we've been eating there ever since I was a teen, she was so nice, I miss her. Making dumplings won't bring her here sadly but at least they might kill the craving I've had for them.

author: UCChI7EjpYWfVAGg4ntHD0LQ
comment: @Kevin Li Thank you. I am happy to hear that.     A local hole-in-the -wall serving Indo-Chinese food  didn't survive the pandemic partly because their costs and therefore prices had gone up. Everyone was eating at home, and restaurants were not allowed to open. I suppose the market for takeaway fell when offices closed.   The local place didn't have cheap dumplings, but they don't sell as much here as in Delhi.

author: UCKrCIiNJPECmeis1MPI7TsQ
comment: @Shinjinee Sen The profits are definitely small per dumping, but selling in bulk does help. Plus, they're raw so a lot less labor goes into it than you think. With the early shortages as people panic bought, they were actually doing quite well and cranking out a few thousand of them a day. With scaled back operating costs, it was enough to keep them afloat until they started taking in phone orders too. At that point, they pretty much stabilized

author: UCOAn1OwGRjOlYMB2FeczheA
comment: @Future Commentary Cook from frozen. The most classic way of cooking is boiling and we just plop them straight into the water. If you're boiling though you can't use Josh's techniques on how to make dumpling skins - it will burst apart if you aggressively freeze. His techniques are what southerners use which do not survive the boiling process. Classic mistakes.  If you want a dumpling that survives, you have to roll those circles out by hand. In doing so, leave more dough towards the center, since that dough will get stretched when you form the dumpling. Dumpling filling itself needs to be more congealed so you shouldn't process it by hand towards the later stages of mixing but rather mix in one direction (with chopsticks). You want it to be more like a meatball.

author: UCoGAhAxmFKpADY1RGexfXvw
comment: You need eggs, milk, cheese, vegetables, herbs so to make a healthier version simply make a few 'smarter' choices fitting your macros / desired calories without giving up too much flavour. E.g. Few egg-whites instead of whole eggs, lower fat or nut-milk (my uncle uses Skyr even, a low-fat high protein yogurt,) a lower-fat cheese and be a little less generous on the oil. Personally I'd not go too crazy and make minimal adjustments, better to keep good flavour and learn portion-control which will help you lose and later maintain a good weight.

author: UClKzIs2N4DBWIChOEiFK-xA
comment: When I collate my recipe notes I use a column for pans. My recipes group ingredients into aggregated stages with a pan size. It's mostly built around square deli containers and yakumi pans, but cambros and specialty containers sometimes factor in.  Anyways you can scan my recipes in the dish room and you know what all you need to collect along with your ingredients at a glance. This is super useful and helps me think clearly about everything I need. I also add some end-notes about the utensils, knives, boards, sheets, pots, bowls and other equipment the recipe will need.  I worked in a kitchen where you had to walk a long distance across other people's stations to get to the walk-in and the pans.  I also started printing small photographs of my station and gluing them into my recipe book.  Also little adhesive tabs help annotate less permanent data like how long each prep task took me last or what by-products and compost my recipe produced and how it dovetailed with other items on my station or someone else's.

The entire reason for that nonsense? Taxes of course. A lot of places exempt certain products from sales tax. Cookies are included in some places, like California. author: UCRvrdTlfdQg8wZdwNSTt9oQ
comment: This is very, very too much extra! I‚Äôm sure it absolutely delicious but most people are going to want a more humble gumbo. The thing I love about making gumbo it that it‚Äôs relatively inexpensive but truly delicious. I use homemade chicken stock (I have never seen beef used), get rid of the lobster use the crab only if affordable but I usually just use chicken, keep the shrimp and andouille, use less file‚Äô powder and do everything else the same. The Cajun spice mixture is almost exactly what I use in mine. I also use the chocolate Roux and  Worcestershire sauce. Okra‚Äôs sliminess can be cured by boiling separately rinsing it and then frying in oil draining on paper towels and then people can add it if they want. Making it this way makes way less slimy and adding it at the last moment also keep it from messing with the gumbo‚Äôs texture. Love the show but I also love gumbo staying humble  too much not to comment!

author: UCScsS5suUd_zb0BrmAgykeg
comment: I'm almost completely blind (and also lack a good sense of smell), but I manage to do most of my cooking just fine. There are lots of tasks and strategies I just sort of use instinctively to accomplish several tasks without needing to look at what I'm doing. For example, the stove has little bumps for different temps, measuring cups have physical lines I can feel, I chop in a way where I can feel where the knife is, etc My family was always too scared to really teach me how to cook until one day my grandma just said screw it, you're gonna learn how to make Gumbo today. Since then, I've been cooking all the time and watching videos like yours and Babbish's have been invaluable for someone struggling with visual impairment.

author: UC-OqYuhoWbVY2cIY9fheSzw
comment: @Abhijeet Das do not assume that blind means complete lack of eyesight. So honestly, this is a question that reflects ignorance. There are plenty of people who are blind and you would never know it because they do not use a cane, a guide dog, nor do they have any of the obvious signs that the media portrays blind people having. Less than 10% of blind people do not have any vision.

author: UCIfIz-lbUh24d72oG5Icwrg
comment: Hey Josh!  I've been watching your videos for a long time and would absolutely love to see you making and trying one of my favorite brazilian deserts: Brazilian Rain Cakes (Bolinhos de chuva).  It's a sweet fried dough that my granny would always make to me when she was alive.  If you want to give it a try, here's the recipe:  1 cup Flour 1 cup Milk 2 tablespoons Sugar 2 tablespoons Cornstarch 2 eggs 1 tablespoon Baking Powder  -Mix everything in a bowl using a whisk -Use a spoon to drop the mixture into the hot oil, try to make it a rounded shape - Fry until golden brown and drop it on some sugar+cinnamon mixture.  Enjoy!

author: UC0Od6X-3wo6crkly9LF8l3g
comment: I recommend to you the Delish channel on Youtube, with June's "Budget Eats" videos.  She's a Chinese American lady who does videos where she shows how to make a week's worth of meals for $20 (She lives in NYC.).  She uses pantry items, like spices, mayo, and things like that to add to the items she's purchased, but it is usually not more than what most of us already have in our pantry.  She also has some videos where she does not use anything that she didn't include in the price, even cooking oil.  She recently did some videos for what you could make with foods commonly given in food pantry boxes, where she didn't include any additional pantry or grocery items at all.  This guy focuses more on making your food look posh, but June focuses on what is going to be affordable and delicious.  She also has an amazing personality.

author: UCEVl91c59zC6Q69KeePAchA
comment: Ok I'm bored so here's the actual price including cooking equipment* (I'm British so prices are in pounds but I converted at end):  - Mayo 1.75 - Siracha (430ml) 2.60 - 3 garlic 0.90 - Table salt 0.90 - Rice vinegar 2.00 - Short grain rice (Sushi rice) 1.65 - rice cooker shown (I think it's the Zojirushi) 181.99 - 8" Bouillon Strainer Extra Fine Mesh 1 (1) 24.99 - White cabbage 0.80 - Adjustable Mandoline Slicer 25.97 - carrots 0.40 (you'll have enough mayo, garlic and salt from previous purchase so we won't add them again)  - white vinegar 1.25 - Soy sauce 1.87 - Ginger 1.00 - Veg oil 2.25 (same garlic still) -  Sugar 0.65 (same soy sauce and white vinegar) - Corn starch 1.92 - The Medium Long Konro Grill 499.00 -Charcoal 9.99 - Chicken thighs 1.80 - AP flour 1.55 - Soda water 0.60 - Butternut squash 1.50 - Sweet onion 1.30 - broccoli 0.70 - Giant cooking pot 10.00 (use leftover veg oil for frying I guess??) - That 5 section Black bento with red inside 28.00  "Extras": - Green onion 0.99 - togarashi spice 2.95 - furikake 2.70  TOTAL (WITHOUT EXTRAS NOR COOKING EQUIPMENT) = ¬£27.39 OR $37.95 TOTAL (WITH EXTRAS) = ¬£34.03 TOTAL (WITH COOKING EQUIPMENT NO EXTRAS) = ¬£834.72 OR $1122.28 TOTAL (WITH EXTRAS AND COOKING EQUIPMENT) = ¬£841.36 OR $1131.21  This ain't meant to offend but rather shed light on total cost and the problem in this video and others like it. Sure this bento won't cost too much to those who have half these ingredients lying about (sauces, ginger, garlic etc) and you'll have extras of those ingredients bought for this but those of use who don't, either through taste or price, it racks up, and extra most likely will go to waste. It's pretty ridiculous to walk into a shop and ask for 60g of mayo, so why price it as if we could do so?  It'd be nice if you could do a meal with the whole price? But that won't end up as classy will it?  Extra Notes: I included items such as salt and sauces cause not everyone is going to have those sauces, most people will have one or the other but not all. I personally only have hot sauce and salt.  I also included cooking equipment as it affects taste, and he didn't show alternatives. *I didn't include every single bit of equipment, just the bits I believe most people won't own/anything special, like a rice cooker or a giant pot (looking at hungry collage students)  EDIT: thanks @Colin for correction in a calculation! EDIT 2: Added Charcoal for Kenro grill to calculations it's included in the total with equipment, thanks for reminding me @xpierogix also apparently the average cost of water in the USA is $1.50 per 1,000 gallons, $117.65 per month for electricity so add those if you wish. As for labour costs I have no clue how to calculate that, my best guess would be the US minimum wage $7.25 per hour and times that by how many hours this'll take. My assumption will be at least 2 hours? If you use you're time wisely. So that'll be $14.50 added on. @Sydney Studds

author: UCyMsOubpHgpsQ8BDVWhnQow
comment: Its pretty easy to guess if you divide everything he does in simple steps. Prep is basically about cutting cabbage and carrot which you can do with a grater in like 10 minutes + 5 minutes for whatever tempura veggies you want , washing rice and putting it in a cooker/pan and forgetting about it can be parallelized with cooking your chicken and frying your tempura. That meal can be done in as long as 40 minutes (an hour if you count cleaning), this is far from unreasonable for a home cooked meal. Also, these videos are not like say, chef johns recipes. Its more of a series guidelines. If you dont have that spice he mentions just do away with it and find some kind of replacement. If you don't like teriyaki sauce just do an indian style chicken curry. You dont need to do a presentation or bbq meat if you cant do it. Thats just joshua flexing his skills.If it aint easy for you to get boneless thighs then either cook bone in or sliced chicken breast. In turn you can save a lot of time by simplifying a lot of the meals. You can make even cheaper bento boxes by being reusing vegetables smartly. E.g making caramelized onions from the leftovers of the tempura onion, using the leftover chicken fat.  As for "time is money", well thats litterally the whole point. He is showing you how to make a meal that would cost way more for way cheaper. But the counterpart is that you have to invest time for planning and cooking. Thus converting money you cant spend on free time you can spend.  Finally, making bento is a leisurely activity. We make this shit because we want a full meal to enjoy for a special occasion. Unless you have a houseperson fully dedicated to make full dishes theres no point in wasting half of your cooking time deepfrying veggies. Dont think of it as a chore. Its something you take time to appreciate making. If you really think of your time as too precious for this then make simpler meal. Rice and chicken and thats it.

author: UC97uUkWVjXbogFWEhLO_hHQ
comment: @Surma Sampo yes, I know what you mean but asking a youtuber to create recipes specifically to be frozen and reheated is just a big ask. if you want to freeze food in your own home, no one is stopping you. but I've never had incredible success freezing food. it's never as good as it was when it was first made, and most precooked food that I've tried to freeze then specifically reheat in the microwave, has turned out like a literal block of ice, rubbery, and barely edible. I just don't think it's fair or reasonable to ask a talented chef to create recipes for crappy frozen food, of all things. if you want frozen food, freeze whatever is sitting in your fridge and see what happens, or, better yet, go to the grocery and buy frozen food specifically made by food scientists to reheat well in the microwave. don't ask a youtube chef to teach you how to make a hungry man microwavable dinner or a tostino's pizza roll. it's ridiculous. Josh is a chef, not Lean Cuisine corporation. how insulting to ask a chef to make frozen dinners. it's just bizarre. if you want a frozen dinner, go buy one dude.

author: UCz2JxkSA_gW0ej5bOWBxXaw
comment: @Scarlett Decent curries, stews and pea & ham soup take hours to make so almost anyone who makes them does so in large qualities and freezes the excess. You pull the frozen meal container out of the freezer and into the fridge the night before you are going to eat it so that it thaws out a bit and then reheat in a pot or microwave. People all over the world have been doing this for decades using cheap freezer safe containers like empty ice cream containers.  These types of foods a very well suited as they only get better with additional cooking time and don't suffer from any of the problems you mention. How did you not know this?

Finally some sriracha on top :D  This is super healthy and tasty. Cost isn't actually very much, salty salad cheese doesn't cost much, hummus is super cheap and so is chicken, I often just get whole rotisserie chicken since it's easy and cheap. And obviously some frozen vegetable mix is also cheap. So overall, everything that fills you up is really cheap products, and salad is very high in protein and fiber so it's optimized for keeping you full longer. And since you are not using lettuce, it has actually plenty of nutrients in it.

author: UC3uXPLH8lYI4badX5t8qHaw
comment: This is one of those things that unfortunately, no one really teaches and that people are just expected to pick up over time. Which you eventually do, as you progress from mastering basic recipes to more complex ones. As you grind through things like stir fries, sheet pan dinners, and pasta, you will get faster with chopping, memorize the approximate ratios of ingredients, and get a feel for where the pauses of activity are in the overall process. That will help you be more efficient as you graduate to multi-course meals (which even though bento technically isn't, it may as well be since it requires making so many different things).   Honestly I do a fair amount of Japanese cooking and I never do tempura in a bento. I'm not gonna tempura fry anything unless I'm doing it at scale for several guests because it is a fuckin' hassle, lol. It's probably gonna get soggy in a sealed tupperware anyway. Teriyaki chicken, rice, and a coleslaw or a green salad with miso dressing is a perfectly legit meal in itself. And you can buy teriyaki sauce instead of making it from scratch, no shame in that I promise.   My top advice for staying organized (having amassed a lot of cooking tools over the years) is that the things you use the most often should be the easiest to reach, and things you use together should be stored next to each other. Prep knives right next to the cutting boards, spatula storage right next to the stove. Spices you don't use very often can go in higher cupboards, baking pans you don't use often can go in that farther-away corner. Put things where they make sense to your brain and you will be able to gather them up faster for prep.

author: UCwnMJKxQq524JnsS3YTEecA
comment: To add to what the others have said, keep an eye out for things to do in parallel instead of doing it step by step. If you are waiting for something to finish you are not using your time well.  Using his recipe as an example: "Teriyaki" sauce - Before adding the cornstarch the sauce simmers for 3 to 5 minutes, meaning you should save time by making the cornstarch mixture while the sauce simmers and not after it is reduced. You might still have enough time to season the chicken and get the grill going. Rice - rice with a rice cooker doesn't require active work so don't eave it for the end, get that rice ready while you do something else. Tempura - If you are going to heat up a buttload of oil like that than you can turn on the heat after cutting the veggies and before making the batter. The batter bowl should be ready by the time the oil is hot. Keep an eye out for smoke and reduce the heat if you struggle with the batter. Spicy Mayo - It's just mixing and whisking, you can do it while you grill the chicken.  Granted, the more things you do at once the more likely you are to do something wrong and burn something, so it's important to know your limits and to understand the recipe. In this case, I would get some more ingredients on the table while my garlic simmers because I've made garlic oil a bunch of times and I don't need to keep an eye on it at all times, but garlic goes from browning to dark and bitter rather quickly so I wouldn't recommend it to you.

author: UCUpbjRsIWY9mRfrOe-Xc1YQ
comment: The french have a term called "mise en place" or "everything in its place". It's a way of making your life much easier. Essentially, you do 100% of the prep work before you begin cooking, so all you have to do is grab your ingredients and go. You can focus your attention on the actual cooking and not worry about preparing other ingredients. You can also prep your ingredients in bulk for future meals, so you have minimal prep work.

author: UCDOEnunFV-6z9PSn86sCOhg
comment: Get out all the ingredients you need for the recipe. Spices and ingredients for things like sauces can be a drain on time, so let's work on that. To make it quicker, group together ingredients with the same quantities - it's not that uncommon, and that can save you time. Group these ingredients on your table by proximity. Does a sauce require 1/2 tsp of minced garlic and 1/2 tsp of sesame seeds? Then put your sesame seed container next to a bulb of garlic, like, noticeably closer than usual in order to indicate they're a group. Prepare these ingredients together, i.e., resist checking back to the recipe until you're done prepping with the group. When you're done with a group of ingredients, put them away.  Prepare cold dishes to a meal before the warm dishes. Cold dishes will be ready whenever you're done; the opposite isn't true.  Wash dishes when you're really not doing anything and your currently cooking ingredients don't require all of your attention.

Save the leftover rice for fried rice the next day. Chilli also freezes well and is fairly cheap per serving especially if you make your beans from dry. author: UCs57mP-lpfXEpAgvGbMedxA
comment: For once, I have a (minor) disagreement with Papa: your batter is too thick. Cr√™pe batter has to be very, very runny. Yours is still creamy. A 2:1 ratio of liquid (in mL, not counting the eggs) to flour (in grams) is a minimum (in cups it'd be roughly 1.5:1 I guess), and even that can be too thick... I'd rather go for 2.5:1. There's nothing worse than thick cr√™pes that set too soon before they spread. If however your batter is liquid enough, your pan hot enough and appropriately greased, then you'll get really crispy edges, dotted with small holes, like "cr√™pes dentelle", and a thin, pliable center.

author: UCYmm-3lvqHH15Y6G6iJGheg
comment: You can make smooth crepe batter without putting it through a fine mesh strainer, my guy... Also, use warm milk, not cold, and I recommend whisking it until smooth after adding only half the milk. You can also skip adding the sugar. If you are putting on sweet toppings, the contrast is wonderful! Not everything has to be sweet! If you want to experiment with flavor in your cr√™pe, try mixing different types of flavor. My father likes half white, half buckwheat when he makes his.  It is most recommended to make your batter the night before. In this case, the warm milk isn't necessary; it's a shortcut if you are making the batter in the same morning. If you aren't making it the night before, you also must let the batter sit out for at least fifteen minutes.  Finally, you gotta work on your technique a little my guy. The pan should be moving as you ladle batter onto it to have a truly even distribution. A good cr√™pe doesn't have that thicker circle of batter in the center, but is the same thin consistency all the way across, with only the very fringes being thinner (and crispy), as it's unavoidable.  Edit: I think you need to add more milk. Looking at how it spreads in the pan, your batter is too thick!

author: UCYmm-3lvqHH15Y6G6iJGheg
comment: @Ivana P√°vkov√° Oh, my father would always use a mixer, and that was part of the difference noticed when I tried without letting it rest! I personally just whisk by hand. I'll have to try not letting it rest sometime and see if there's many air bubbles; when I made some today, even after letting it rest for fifteen minutes, there were still some, especially in the first 2-3. I should probably adjust my whisking technique to introduce less air into the batter...

author: UCiq__4w1q4gNMPDT3aEuBaw
comment: @Godminnette2 I mean I can imagine that if you start with a super liquidy batter it would still be liquid enough the next day, but you wouldn't be able to prevent the fermentation and slight sourness of the batter, imo. But that doesn't make the batter inedible, it just isn't traditional ü§∑üèª‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è And yeah his batter I'd 100% too thick. If I recall correctly (it's been a few years), we used to use 1:4 ratio of flour:milk.  P.S. Where I see the benefit of resting the batter is of you use a blender or mixer to make it, because that whips a lot of air into the batter. In that case, resting is a necessity to prevent bubbles in the final cr√™pe!

author: UCYmm-3lvqHH15Y6G6iJGheg
comment: @Ivana P√°vkov√° Honestly, I've actually never done it myself. My extended family likes to do it, though my father usually doesn't bother with it. However, they are able to make razor-thin crepes with it still. Perhaps their batter is simply made a certain way? Or they add a little more milk the next morning. Maybe I'll check with them and see.  I, however, do notice a difference between making it fresh and waiting fifteen minutes. Perhaps it's just placebo. I'd be interested in people doing little blind tests with this.  Do you at least agree that his batter is too thick? He uses a 1:1 flour to milk ratio...

author: UCiq__4w1q4gNMPDT3aEuBaw
comment: I see all these comments recommending to let the batter rest. I worked as a cr√™pier in a Parisian cr√™perie. Having gone through buckets of cr√™pe batter, I don't see any difference between batter that is fresh or 15mins or 1h old. Batter left in the fridge overnight starts to ferment and become thick and slightly sour (you'll know bc it creates bubbles when fried up). Although it doesn't taste bad, it's impossible to make thin cr√™pes with it and we'd always toss it. So I'm not so sure about leaving it overnight.

author: UC7rXucF5eZhnAG_yUj1aX0g
comment: I had a good basic crepe recipe that is 1 cup flour, 2 eggs eggs, 1 cup milk, 2 tbls. melted butter, and salt. I had no complaints but decided to try one with differing amounts of the same 5 ingredients with the addition of water and the insistence that you let the batter sit in the fridge for at least one day, better yet, two. I used it immediately the first time and it was a little better than my original recipe but I decided to let it sit the second time since the recipes‚Äôs author so strongly insisted on it.  OMG. The crepes were _sublime._ Not only is the flavor better, the texture improved 10 fold. It‚Äôs softer in a tender way, not squishy. I guess I should make the first batter and let it sit to see if the water is necessary, but I haven‚Äôt been able to go back to it. Josh,  have you let your crepe batter sit at least a day and if so, does it greatly improve the taste and texture of your crepes?

author: UC9jsvcdqk_KjDHiP_bRB2og
comment: I used to be a supervisor at A&W. Believe me, we did everything we physically could to try and make the food decent... but during Covid, upper management made massive price cuts. I'm talking labour percentage of 11-14% and our manager getting written up and screamed at on the phone if it went higher. Any restaurant owner worth their salt will tell you that this is COMPLETELY INSANE. Everyone quit in April, starting with our manager, and including myself, because we were being pushed to work unpaid overtime just in order to keep things up to standard. I was a supervisor and I didn't want anyone getting food poisoning, so I was going in unpaid after hours (in exchange for food that my manager slipped me) trying to clean the place up because having one cook and one cashier on a Friday night means that nobody has time to clean. And my manager came in, unpaid, on CHRISTMAS DAY to clean because that was the only day of the year where there weren't any customers. One day my manager finally went rogue and authorized for a bunch of us to stay late and get paid to deep clean the place (because the HEALTH BOARD told her to), and head office screamed at her over the phone. I heard it. She told them that she needed more labour to get the place up to health board standards, and they punished her for it by cutting our hours even more. After that we all coordinated finding other jobs, and one by one, all quit over the course of a month.  If you ever go to an A&W during rush hour and you only see two people working, or if the line is around the building... go somewhere else. If you must go there, try to keep your focus on the popular, standard items that sell quickly, and you'll be more likely to get it fresh. And please... go easy on those kids. They're trying their best out there.  I know this video was about BK and not A&W but... I just had to get that out there.

author: UCrMHNbWQZNSvxID-M6F8BLw
comment: Love the video, as always :D  Some Mexican tips:  -You can blister the jalape√±o with the direct flame from the stove, gently turning it around as the sides cook - The are two trends of chilaquiles: soft chilaquiles (like the rojos that you cooked) and crunchy chilaquiles (you don't cook the corn chips in the sause, instead, the salsa is poured over the totopos (corn chips).  Normally, the soft chilaquiles are put inside a bread (bolillo), making a torta de chilaquiles - You can whatever meat you like, chicken, steak, shrimps (yup, that's typical from the Mexican coast). Normally, the chilaquiles are served with purple onion (diced), Mexican beans (not chili beans), sour cream and cheese (queso freso)

author: UCq3w4h4VWW7uXJbdAfALPmA
comment: You inspired me with several of your Asian Specialty dishes, so much so that I made a much needed visit to my local Asian / Oriental (their name not me being insensitive) grocery store.   I picked up pantry items not found or as fresh as those found at my regular grocery chain store. Organic soy sauce from Japan, double black soy sauce and toasted sesame seed oil,  Shao Hsing Rice Cooking Wine 12% alcohol, all from China.  Oyster sauce from Thailand, so fresh and delicious and finally, Red Boat brand Fish Sauce first cold pressed from vietnam.  The fish sauce is so fresh, so fragrant that I will never buy the stale smaller bottle in the chain grocery store ever again!  I order Szechuan peppercorns, green and red, so I had those already in my panty.  The Chinese chilli crisp was just a bonus because it's just so dang good on scrambled eggs in the morning.   All these fresh ingredients have elevated every dish to something to truly enjoy and make "But-Better" at home.

author: UCptdnagOnSiYgEttB4JfH5Q
comment: The secret to great kung pao chicken is using some fermented bean paste,  just stir it in the hot oil for a minute or two before you stir fry the veggies. Also, to balance it out add a tablespoon or two of brown sugar. Also, if you add one egg white to the chicken marinate, it will help lock in moisture. And for a more hearty kung pao chicken, just add some more chopped veggies. I like it with zucchini and red bell pepper.

author: UChpgU06pzFxVCroDMXaK3Og
comment: Put it in a Tupperware and store it in the fridge, this can last up to 3-4 days. To reheat, simply bust out a wok and add some water to act as a buffer while the chicken heats up so the sauce doesn't get too thick. Or just put it in the microwave, that works too, though the chicken will be a little dry inside.

author: UCbS15zJXywRrcW0bjIewiFQ
comment: i put it in the fridge and reheat it at top of the rice in a rice cooker while cooking rice, saves time and a lot of cleaning. Nearly all cooked food are good min. 2 days in fridge.

author: UCGP9e6EI3FmxM-9sBng0trg
comment: After you cook it, portion them into storage containers right away to cool down. Then put them in the fridge if you'll eat them in 3-4 days, or put in freezer for if you'll eat them farther in the future. I like to freeze so that I don't eat leftovers many days in a row. To thaw, just take out and microwave for 3 mins or whatever.

author: UCMQ1VvpGNiPkAZv7ZeuM1NA
comment: Some things csn be substituted.  Like if someone has a peanut allergy, you can switch for cashews from a company that explicitly states they only process cashews.  There should be resources available online that can inform you on what can be substituted for what when dealing with allergies.   You may still not be able to make everything you want, but you should be able to expand your cooking options some.

author: UC0rxr8mRTIPz07tHD8y78QQ
comment: It's also common to use cashews instead of peanuts, they're a bit sweeter and softer, and a better balance to the spice. Additionally, add in regular onions (sliced in chunks) and ginger (large slices). Fry them off with the other vegetables.

author: UCJMqgOkMBoYdTkAqBDQNL5g
comment: While Shaoxing imparts a very nice fragrance, it's main purpose is either to 1) cool down the wok during a stir fry and/or 2) remove "gaminess" and "fishiness" (I put those in quotes because there's direct translation of the word ËÖ• which generally refers to an almost muddy or metallic unpleasant odor or taste found in all animals and even some plants). I have a lot of Chinese Muslims in my family so they can't use Shaoxing wine for religious reasons, they substitute it with the steeping liquid of ginger and Szechuan peppercorns.

author: UC97uUkWVjXbogFWEhLO_hHQ
comment: here's something important: I highly recommend that NO ONE fucks around with dry lye at home, even if Josh makes light of it. little tip from a chemical engineer. it's way too caustic, and possibly explosive, to have lying around your home, especially if you have kids or pets. it's just not worth it, and I'm a little mad at how casually he addressed the dangers of dry lye.   if your child swallows lye, even multiple surgeries may not correct the damage. it can melt throat tissue and cause the throat to permanently close. lye and water create an exothermic reaction, the fumes of which can be dangerous if inhaled. the hydrogen gas produced from contact between lye water and certain metals can be flammable, creating an explosion if you light a gas stove, or torch in your kitchen, following contact. it's not something to take lightly, and I don't advise anyone buy dry lye and mix it with water in their home just to make a couple stupid pretzels. it's not worth it - please don't be casual about lye usage at home.  "Breathing in sodium hydroxide causes irritation of eyes, nose and throat, cough, chest tightness, headache, fever and confusion. In serious cases lye inhalation causes damage to the airways". (gov.uk)  "The combination of aluminum and sodium hydroxide results in a large production of hydrogen gas: 2Al(s) + 6NaOH(aq) ‚Üí 3H2(g) + 2Na3AlO3(aq). Hydrogen gas is explosive; mixing lye (sodium hydroxide) and aluminum in a closed container is therefore dangerous. In addition to aluminum, lye (sodium hydroxide) and/or caustic potash (potassium hydroxide) may also react with magnesium, zinc (galvanized), tin, chromium, brass, and bronze to produce hydrogen gas and is therefore dangerous." many people have kitchen implements made of various metals, including tin. covering with certain types of aluminum foil is equally unsafe. aluminum cans are unsafe.  remember those cinnamon sugar pretzels? lye water and sugar create carbon monoxide. you read that correctly. this is the reason Josh couldn't sprinkle the pretzels fresh out of the lye water with sugar, like he did with the salted pretzels. I wish he had explained that to the viewers. if you try this at home, you might have been tempted to dunk it in sugar before the oven to save time. though the CO production would be minimal just from dunking in sugar and then baking, it's still not a good idea to have a bowl of sugar near lye water. if you drop a significant amount of sugar in lye water, and you don't know that it's dangerous, you may just leave it to clean up later, right? little do you know, it's producing carbon monoxide the entire time. the warmer the water gets, the quicker it's producing CO.  here's the link to the website of a lye maker, advising consumers of the dangers associated with lye, in case you're still thinking of buying some and keeping it around your house: http://www.certified-lye.com/safety.html  oh, and you also can't throw the rest of the lye you bought in the trash, or down the drain, after using it once to make pretzels. it's corrosive. "Lye is considered hazardous waste and is subject to federal, state and local disposal regulations". so once you have it, you have to find a way to dispose of the remainder according to your state and local laws, just keep storing it in your home forever, or take a risk and try to neutralize it at home with a weak acid like vinegar and just see how it goes. all dry lye is a little different, so it's hard to know whether it's neutralized or not without testing the pH. it's not a good idea to just pour it out in your backyard either... hopefully that goes without saying. it will kill your plants, and it's still corrosive. like I said, not worth it. just use baking soda instead, or make another dessert. cake is delicious. you don't need pretzels made with dry lye at home üò°it's a disaster waiting to happen. that's the bottom line.

author: UCywlhvBVTjOgXJ6aRTGPh8g
comment: heres the thing, part of the reason Aunty Annes isnt crusty is because they dont use lye water. I know I used to work for them as a kid 20 years ago. They use baking soda water which is safer but does not make the same kind of crust because its not as alkaline.  You can make a closer version without lye water but with baking soda though. Just bake the baking soda. Its the same technique used for home ramen and bagel making. Its not AS good as lye, but its a fuck ton safer (I'd still wear gloves though just cause its not good for your hands). Put a box of baking soda on a foil lined baking sheet and bake at 275 for a hour. Let cool and bottle up in a air tight container. Lix 2/3rds in with 2 cups water and boom, close approximation of lye water without the skin melting lye laying around that you will never use (since lye is not common at all anymore in the household like it was 60+ years ago.

author: UCnRihA2r_JxnNFeFEN7f0rw
comment: Anyone who was curious, the lye is entirely optional.  For those wondering what I mean: bake roughly 1/2 cup of baking soda (110g) in your oven at 285 F / 140 C for 1 hour and then immediately dump it into 2 cups (473mL) of waiting water in your container you'd be otherwise lye bathing in.   Then make your pretzels exactly the same way except you let them soak in the baking soda bath for about 3 minutes before continuing with the rest of the recipe.   This is far less caustic, doesn't matter if it gets on your hands, is food safe from the get go even if you screw up your ratio, and won't stain your counters/cutting boards/pans/whatever. It is still pretty basic so it can burn you, but far less likely compared to lye and it's an ingredient basically all of you have in your house.

author: UCsMq6LiaAQA0BUK6GmCfY-w
comment: As a fellow cook who's lived in Thailand, THIS IS A GREAT RECIPE! I have some notes about things you *can* do differently, mainly 1) the meats can be *any* variety, there are pork and chicken and beef and so on variations of Tom Yums, 2) the official term for the coconut milk version of the tom yum soup is 'tom yum nam khon' ('boiled sour/water coconut' approx translation) as opposed to 'tom yum nam sai' (boiled sour water clear) the default.  the 3) tip actually comes from Vietnamese cooking, for your lobster alternate; in Viet food, they will take a sliver out of a sugar cane, and wrap meats around this and cook it (usually deep fry) so that the sweetness of the cane infuses the meat, ingredient tip 4) about being able to replace the kefir lime leaf with lime zest (mostly, it's an 80% coverage thing that real pros may or may not be able to spot if you do it to their soup) and ALSO NOT adding lime juice UNTIL THE END because boiled lime juice becomes very bitter and unpalatable, and finally 5) while the accent is cute, the thai word 'tom' is pronounced like the english 'dome' (as in, inverted half circular type of roof structure), where 'yum' more typically rhymes with 'nom'  as in 'nomnomnomnomnom DELICIOUS'. (if you care, this is down to some strange phonetic rules for how to spell thai in english, whch is difficult since their sounds are halfway between all the english sounds, and so the letters don't match precisely, but the 'h' addition is to make it a 'hard'/'aspirated' consonant, so 'thai' is a hard T 'Tai', were the 't' normally officially denotes a 'dt' or harder 'th' sound, which is halfway between the thai T and D sounds that english has both of) (basically don't worry about the accent, everybody who hears you will just go "OH HAHAHA that's how anglophones say it huh")

author: UCny1yBWEuThaD73-oKTQ_0w
comment: Thai-Lao German here with a major hack (courtesy of my mom) on using NPP if you are afraid of that heavenly stuff spoiling while not wanting Tom (though I have no clue who would).  Put it thin (or thicc to your liking, recomennd starting thin) as butter replacement on your (preferably good German rye, sourdough is fine) bread. Yes. You read that.  trust me and add some (lots) leafy salad (I prefer romaine and rocket, Iceberg waters down so much), a slice of cheese or sausage (HQ cured ham is esp nice) for an incredible open sandwich!  Sunnysideup egg is great for breakfast/brunch.  If you're indulging, you might want to add cilantro and thai basil to your greens, which makes it really kick!

comment: We don't need a "but easier" series. We need a "don't be lazy" series.  How do you expect homemade donuts to be made easier? You can either buy a prepackaged dough or make it yourself.  There are no shortcuts for making dough. lol  FYI, I was making yeast doughs back when I was 10 years old. If you are above the age of 10, you have no excuses for not being able to do this.  The problem with most young people is that their attention span is very short.  They want food to be quick while they watch something on their phone & text others.  Turn off all your distracting devices, measure out everything beforehand & just make the focking dough god dammit.

author: UCy0J0z3X7X5ETNRwyw_CT4g
comment: Really nice sandwich, would love to eat that. But here in Vietnam it is actually cheaper to buy banh mi from street vendors. Also we dont use baguette, the bread is much lighter and has a really crispy skin. The roasted pork belly is usually chopped up into cubes and slathered with a Vietnamese version of BBQ sauce (which is thick and syrupy). The cucumber is cut into thin logs so it runs the entire length of the bread (VNmese cucumbers are smaller and crunchier). Just my 2 cents as a Vietnamese who eats banh mi religiously.

author: UC9S1pa_u8Vh12lZlRIPP1aQ
comment: This looks delicious! One minor criticism: The bread in banh mi seems to be substituted by regular baguettes in other countries, but it's not ideal. Thinner baguette-style bread with very airy insides, like the ones common in Vietnam, does a better job at limiting the ratio of "just plain, dry bread" to "flavorful, moist components" in a sandwich.

author: UCwYnmQsl8aQVAEaCEtVDWDg
comment: Correct. I joined an online learning course fom a banhmi baker in Can Tho to learn his recipe (just my homebaking leisure time during the lockdown). It‚Äôs not easy to figure out the right recipe without bread improver for banhmi at home (and the tip is using eggs to replace bread improvers üòã). What we aim to achieve is very soft, light and fluffy interior (the dough needs to be needed until it passes window test), very thin and crispy skin, baked at high temperature with lost of moist that the skin is supposed to crack itself upon coming out of oven üòã Not all bakeries in Vietnam have good banhmi though. Some put too much bread improvers or additives that make the bread texture/ taste unoriginal and it rises 4-5 times in size during proofing; purely for seller‚Äôs profit purpose.

author: UCQUX9LDUrt5H6pQYY9Dpw1g
comment: In all my years of home baking, Vietnamese style baguettes is still something I have yet to completely nail 100%. I have learned so much through all of my failures in trying making one and yet, even the fluffiest, airyest rustic breads I've made still can't quite compare to the crust and texture of a Vietnamese baguette. I feel like the only way to get there is to use the exact steam ovens used by those bakeries and I'm not ready to make that investment just for this.

author: UCoHQDuCM3WpSILInyDBfX5g
comment: Real nice work! Banh Mi is done differently for everyone, including vendors. Some use Butter, Some use Pate, Some use Pate AND Mayo/Butter. Some use multiple meat combinations. It's all great long as it's got dat fusion of spicy, sweet, tang, salty umaminess.

author: UC6J4VLQZ_yZHaE3gzINLe-w
comment: A traditional french baguette can be a little too tough for a banh mi sandwich. The inside can be anything, most really don't care, but the bread is essential.  Light and crispy on the outside, but not as crunchy as a baguette. And so fluffy on the inside that it collapses a little when stacking the ingredients, and the crust creates a sort of shell that keeps the ingredients from falling out when eating. A baguette can be harder on the outside and the bread inside might have too strong of a gluten development and not collapse enough.  The ingredients might slide out when eating.   The rest of the ingredients look pretty delicious. They'd make a killer banh mi.

author: UCyFnznnjZ1fdqZ7d7deF8QA
comment: You've nailed the fillings except you must have pate...really essential.  After eating hundreds of Banh Mi in Little Saigon in Westminster, CA., your biggest miss is the bread. French baguette is wrong. Just like a Philly cheesesteak or a Po boy in New Orleans, it's all about the bread. You've got a huge Vietnamese population in Texas to learn from. I'd love to see an episode baking a Vietnamese style loaf. I've never been able to reproduce one myself.  IMHO, you can take a lot of license with the fillings of a Bahn Mi, but you must have the right bread, pate, pickled carrots and daikon. Go crazy after that. If you could do a "But Better" episode for a Bahn Mi roll I'd be eternally grateful. BTW, I love your book. Giving copies to family for Christmas. Keep it up!

author: UCdvpwNJUOkEcvrRYlHKYBMw
comment: For that "puffy" effect you were looking for on the pork skin, next time, prior to salting and drying, try scoring the skin with a really sharp knife of exacto blade in a crisscross pattern, with cuts just deep enough to pierce the skin down to, but not though the subcutaneous fat layer underneath. Then rub the salt in and dry in the fridge as you described. Then, end the last 5-10 minutes in the oven with a full on broil, keeping an eye in it that it doesn't burn. Watch that skin puff and pop!

author: UCnWKLFyd4mUIZOvj6Q64J9w

author: UCQ2r3co_0hmeSKYJDWkOKCA
comment: I am damn proud that our culinary made it out there. although it's far. and i mean FARRRR from a normal b√°nh m√¨ here in Viet Nam but yours looks damn delish. we dont really use baguettes but a traditional bread which is super airy and fluffy with super crispy skin that could actually cut the roof of your mouth lol. and we just throw random stuff that is in our fridge in there. you have meat? good. use meat. you dont? heck. use an egg. throw in some pate. shredded pork jerky (i think. i dont even know what it's called in english) is a great choice. and there's no "secret sauce" to the b√°nh m√¨. squirt in some chilli sauce and boom. that's the secret sauce. b√°nh m√¨ is actually just bread. the filling, be creative. there's no best b√°nh m√¨. it's how you want it to be.
